			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Corduba adolescentulus vtroq[ue] erat egregius: et arguta
						ratiocinatione pra[e] ca[e]teris: et multiplici artiu[m] instructu
					</marginalia_text>
					<location name="Corduba"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						super omnes. Proximus
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						illi Fortius. Fortio Ramus:
						Ramo Freigius: Freigio Gregoris: Gregorio =
						<!-- Continues onto facing page, head, Ha2.135r -->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Joachim Fortius Ringelberg"/>
					<person name="Petrus Ramus"/>
					<person name="Johann Thomas Freigius"/>
					<person name="Pierre Gregoire"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A very young man in Corduba was excellent in both disciplines;
				and with clever reasoning, he was beyond the other men; and instructed by various men 
				of the arts, he was above all men. Fortius was next to him, and Ramus next Fortius.
				Next to Ramus was Freigius, and next to Freigius Gregoire. Next to Gregoire
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="IT">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						doni significatiuivi: com&egrave; Amore
						dipinto con vn fiore in vna mano, et vn pesce nell'altra
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Amore"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="vn fiore in"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="pesce nell'altra"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						per significare,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						che gli signoreggia la terra, e 'l mare.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="la terra"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="e'l mare"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						nel [quarto] di Guazzo.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Stefano Guazzo"/>
					<book title="The civil conversation"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Meaningful gifts, such as Love painted with a flower in hand and a fish in the other,
				which means that he rules over land and sea.
				In Guazzo's fourth book.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Multi hodi&egrave; Academici, volu[n]t esse Luciani Rhetores: Turnebi
						artifices: Aula[e] philosophi: Agrippa[e] scientiarum professores:
						pra[e]sertim maxim&egrave; fallacium, vtilium, nobilium;
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Lucian"/>
					<person name="Adrianus Turnebus"/>
					<person name="Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa"/>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						summ&egrave;q[ue] pragmaticarum. Pulchrum laudo: non probo vanum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Today, many academics want to be like Lucian's rhetoricians, Turnebus' artists, philosophers of the court,
				or Agrippa's scientific professors, especially and chiefly concerning deceits, useful matters, noble things; <!-- CG: Not sure what to do with 'fallacium, utilium' etc. --> <!--JG: I don't get this either. Combination of words (and their meaning) don't seem to 'fit' either. I'll ask a specialist-->
				and, most of all, pragmatic activities. I praise the beautiful man, but I do not approve the vain one.  
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Semper ad rem: vt Tempestas.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Always focused on the thing at hand, as a tempest.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Pra[e]sentior, et viuidior:
						argutior, et amabilior: quisquis
						maxim&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				More present and more vivid;
				more clever and more loving;
				everyone to the highest degree.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
